  "format": "A spoiler-light first look at Licorice Pizza, then Sean and Amanda rank all nine Paul Thomas Anderson features.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Licorice Pizza’",
      "note": "spoiler-light first look",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Licorice Pizza",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "PTA back in the San Fernando Valley, 1973: a 15-year-old hustler (Cooper Hoffman, son of Philip Seymour Hoffman) and a drifting 25-year-old (Alana Haim), both first-time actors. Sean and Amanda read it as a hangout movie in the Altman/Hal Ashby line rather than another argument about American capitalism, and hold the review until it opens wide. Bradley Cooper, Sean Penn, Tom Waits, Benny Safdie and a scene-stealing Harriet Sansom Harris in support; a Wings needle-drop lands as the big cue."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "ranking",
      "heading": "The Paul Thomas Anderson Rankings",
      "note": "all nine features, best first",
      "subject": "Paul Thomas Anderson",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "There Will Be Blood",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "No. 1, no debate for Sean. The sum of his powers arriving at the right moment, a 20th-century story about wanting more and more without knowing why."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Master",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "No. 2. The one Sean still can't fully solve, and he ranks it above Boogie Nights for exactly that reason: nobody else could have made it. A film about what happens between men."
        },
        {
          "title": "Boogie Nights",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "No. 3. The movie that made Sean a movie person, but he reads it as PTA working with Scorsese's tools before he found his own."
        },
        {
          "title": "Phantom Thread",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 4. The turn toward romance and the Vicky Krieps two-hander; the diner-order scene as the most yearning thing in his filmography."
        },
        {
          "title": "Magnolia",
          "year": 1999,
          "note": "No. 5. 189 minutes of everything at once: reach exceeding grasp, but Tom Cruise's performance still stops them cold."
        },
        {
          "title": "Licorice Pizza",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "No. 6, with recency bias acknowledged: a filmmaker who finally knows how to make movies. Sean takes it over Punch-Drunk Love on the strength of the Alana character."
        },
        {
          "title": "Punch-Drunk Love",
          "year": 2002,
          "note": "No. 7. The hard left off Magnolia and a genuine experiment; the Adam Sandler performance nobody else could have pulled out of him."
        },
        {
          "title": "Inherent Vice",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "No. 8. The Pynchon detour: funny, sprawling, closest in shape to Licorice Pizza, but the big feelings never quite land. Sean wonders about the Robert Downey Jr. version that almost was."
        },
        {
          "title": "Hard Eight",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "No. 9 by necessity: the least ambitious and the first, but the writing's already there, with Philip Baker Hall and a young John C. Reilly."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
